{{Infobox person | name = Ram Shankar Tripathi | image = | caption = | birth_date = | birth_place = India | death_date = | death_place = | occupation = Scholar of Buddhism, Sanskrit, Pali | spouse = | children = | parents = | awards = [[Padma Shri]] | website = | imagesize = | restingplace = | restingplacecoordinates = | othername = | yearsactive = | known for = | domesticpartner = }} '''Ram Shankar Tripathi''' is an Indian scholar of Buddhism, editor and author of a large number of texts focusing on Buddhist philosophy and Buddhist Tantra. Partly inspired by Jagannath Upadhyaya, Ram Shankar Tripathi has been instrumental in reviving the study of Buddhist texts among Sanskritist in India and abroad, having taught a vast number of scholars from different parts of the world, and through a long-lasting association with traditional Buddhist scholars, from Tibet, Burma and elsewhere. Much of the important editorial work from the CUTS (former CIHTS) in Sarnath was encouraged and supported by Ram Shankar Tripathi's guidance; several prominent Tibetan Lamas, as well as a good number of contemporary Buddhologists, have studied with him.
He is the former Dean of the Faculty of Śabdavidyā at the [[Central University of Tibetan Studies]].<ref name="CUTS Annual Report">{{cite web | url=http://www.cuts.ac.in/guestsection/annual_report/AnnualReport2010-11Eng.pdf | title=CUTS Annual Report | publisher=Central University of Tibetan Studies | date=2011 | accessdate=February 17, 2016}}</ref> He has served as the Head of the Department of ''Bauddhadarśana'' at the [[Sampurnanand Sanskrit University]].<ref name="Monastic Dialogue - Seminars">{{cite web | url=http://tibethouse.in/content/monastic-dialogue-seminars | title=Monastic Dialogue - Seminars | publisher=Tibet House, New Delhi | date=2015 | accessdate=February 17, 2016}}</ref> He is also associated with the [[Savitribai Phule Pune University]], where he is a visiting faculty of [[Pali]] and Buddhist Studies.<ref name="Collaborative Academic Activities">{{cite web | url=http://www.unipune.ac.in/dept/fine_arts/pali/Pali_webfiles/academic.htm | title=Collaborative Academic Activities | publisher=Savitribai Phule Pune University | date=2016 | accessdate=February 17, 2016}}</ref> He is the author of several books in Hindi and [[Sanskrit]], including ''Sautrāntikadarśanam'',<ref name="Sautrāntikadarsanam">{{cite book | url=http://www.bibliaimpex.com/index.php?p=sr&Uc=8511&l=0 | title=Sautrantikadarsanam | publisher=Central University of Tibetan Studies | author=Ram Shankar Tripathi | year=1990 | pages=682 | isbn=9788187127734}}</ref> and has edited [[Dalai Lama]]'s ''The Path to Tranquility: Daily Meditations'',<ref name="The Path to Tranquility: Daily Meditations">{{cite book | url=http://www.abebooks.com/servlet/BookDetailsPL?bi=8074202046&searchurl=an%3Dram%2520shankar%2520tripathi%26fe%3Don | title=The Path to Tranquility: Daily Meditations | publisher=Penguin Books India | author=Dalai Lama | editor=Ram Shankar Tripathi | translator=Thuptan Chhogdup | year=2012 | isbn=9780143418023}}</ref> among others.<ref name="A Direct Path to the Buddha Within">{{cite web | url=https://books.google.ae/books?id=Eso6AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA566&lpg=PA566&dq=Ram+Shankar+Tripathi&source=bl&ots=GIOVyq7ysf&sig=zwNni5gyIKjcsbRbdiCO-eSrS7k&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi1oazT4v7KAhWHORQKHSzLB084FBDoAQhBMAc#v=onepage&q=Ram%20Shankar%20Tripathi&f=false | title=A Direct Path to the Buddha Within | publisher=Simon and Schuster | date=2016 | accessdate=February 17, 2016}}</ref> ''Hevajratantram: With Muktāvalī Pañjikā of Mahāpaṇḍitācārya Ratnākaraśānti''<ref name="Hevajratantram: With Muktāvalī Pañjikā of Mahāpaṇḍitācārya Ratnākaraśānti">{{cite book | url=http://www.bagchee.com/books/BB3798/hevajratantram-with-muktavali-panjika-of-mahapanditacarya-ratnakarasanti/ | title=Hevajratantram: With Muktavali Panjika of Mahapanditacarya Ratnakarasanti | publisher=Central Institute of Higher Tibetan Studies |author1=Ram Shankar Tripathi |author2=Thakur Sain Negi | year=2001 | pages=335}}</ref> and ''Jainavidyā evaṃ Prākr̥ta''<ref name="Jainavidyā evaṃ Prākr̥ta">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Jainavidy%C4%81_eva%E1%B9%83_Pr%C4%81kr%CC%A5ta.html?id=MbAcAAAAMAAJ | title=Jainavidyā evaṃ Prākr̥ta | publisher=Sampurnanand Sanskrit University |author1=Ram Shankar Tripathi |author2=Gokulacandra Jaina | year=1987 | pages=345}}</ref> are two of his other notable works. His most recent publication is a Sanskrit commentary on the Pramāṇavārttika, Chapter I, offering a comprehensive guide to Dharmakīrti's difficult verses, and being more accessible than the ancient commentaries.
The Government of India awarded him the fourth highest civilian honour of the [[Padma Shri]], in 2009, for his contributions to Literature and Education.<ref name="Padma Awards">{{cite web | url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf | title=Padma Awards | publisher=Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India | date=2016 | accessdate=January 3, 2016}}</ref>
